      <div class="collapse" id="anchor-reviews">
        <section class="anchored-nav-content-section">
          <h2 class="section-heading">Reviews</h2>
          <div class="slider">
              <div>
                <blockquote class="blockquote-review">
                  <div>&quot;How did cultural globalization in the twentieth century travel along such a one-way path? And why is the U.S.&mdash;that globe-bestriding colossus&#160;with more than 700 overseas bases&mdash;so strangely isolated? The answer, Sam Lebovic&rsquo;s new book,&#160;<i>A Righteous Smokescreen</i>,&#160;convincingly argues, largely comes down to American policy in the middle decades of the twentieth century. . . . [Lebovic&#39;s]&#160;approach is wildly innovative and helps us dramatically rethink the postwar US and the limits to the world order it helped construct.&quot;</div>
                </blockquote>
                <p class="blockquote-review-attribution">The New Republic</p>
              </div>
              <div>
                <blockquote class="blockquote-review">
                  <div>&quot;Sophisticated. . . &#160;Lebovic&#39;s prodigious research and effective argument make this an important study for understanding Cold War&ndash;era global culture.&quot;</div>
                </blockquote>
                <p class="blockquote-review-attribution">Choice</p>
              </div>
              <div>
                <blockquote class="blockquote-review">
                  <div>&ldquo;This is an absolutely stupendous book. If you&#39;ve ever wondered how globalization became so asymmetric&mdash;with one country filling the airways with its movies, sports, and news&mdash;Lebovic shows you. <i>A Righteous Smokescreen</i> is a brilliant history of the rise of the United States&rsquo; information empire.&rdquo;</div>
                </blockquote>
                <p class="blockquote-review-attribution">Daniel Immerwahr, author of How to Hide an Empire: A History of the Greater United States</p>
              </div>
              <div>
                <blockquote class="blockquote-review">
                  <div>&ldquo;<i>A Righteous Smokescreen&#160;</i>presents a tightly focused, impeccably documented argument that the United States&rsquo; rhetorical commitment to liberal internationalism after World War II was mere camouflage for its hard-nosed drive toward global dominance. Lebovic crisply deconstructs the pieties about freedom that underpinned Washington&rsquo;s claims to global leadership in the 1940s&mdash;and continue to animate American foreign-policy debates today.&rdquo;</div>
                </blockquote>
                <p class="blockquote-review-attribution">Diana Lemberg, author of Barriers Down: How American Power and Free-Flow Policies Shaped Global Media</p>
              </div>
              <div>
                <blockquote class="blockquote-review">
                  <div>&ldquo;Lebovic&rsquo;s focus on &lsquo;quotidian world-ordering&rsquo; reveals anything but ordinary findings. He convincingly argues for the importance of US institutional politics in the making of cultural globalization, showing how bureaucrats&rsquo; decisions shaped millions of lives in realms as disparate as education, information, and travel. Erudite and accessible at the same time, Lebovic&rsquo;s book revises our understanding of phenomena from passports to the press. Few books show why bureaucrats matter with such verve and precision.&rdquo;</div>
                </blockquote>
                <p class="blockquote-review-attribution">Heidi Tworek, author of News from Germany: The Competition to Control World Communications, 1900–1945</p>
              </div>
              <div>
                <blockquote class="blockquote-review">
                  <div>&ldquo;How free was information in the post-World War II era of US liberal internationalism? In this brilliant, necessary book, Lebovic dispels a smokescreen of lofty, liberatory rhetoric, painstakingly reconstructing and incisively analyzing the political, institutional, and technical hard-wiring of a deeply uneven and unequal global information landscape.<i> A Righteous Smokescreen</i> will be indispensable for historians of US internationalism and media politics, and anyone interested in globalization&rsquo;s past and present.&rdquo;</div>
                </blockquote>
                <p class="blockquote-review-attribution">Paul A. Kramer, author of The Blood of Government: Race, Empire, the United States and the Philippines</p>
              </div>
          </div>
        </section>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="anchored-nav-section">
